[2] USA: Texas case
Date: 6 Oct 2014
Source: NY Times [edited]
http://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/07/us/ebola-patient-in-dallas-still-in-critical-condition-cdc-chief-says.html?_r=0


The Liberian man [now] in critical condition in a Dallas hospital with the Ebola virus is being treated with an experimental antiviral drug, Texas officials said Mon [6 Oct 2014]. Candace White, a spokeswoman for Texas Health Presbyterian Hospital in Dallas, said Monday that the patient, D., was receiving the drug, brincidofovir, after the Food and Drug Administration approved its use on an emergency basis.

Brincidofovir, made by Chimerix of Durham, N.C., is taken orally and is being tested against several common viruses...

--
Ebola patient D.'s passenger health screening form
------------------------------
2 Oct 2014: (Gazettenet) This 2 Oct 2014 photo shows a copy of a passenger health screening form filled out by Ebola patient D., which was obtained by the Associated Press from the Liberia Airport Authority. Liberia plans to prosecute D, who brought Ebola into the U.S., alleging that he lied on a health questionnaire about not having any contact with an infected person, authorities said Thursday, 2 Oct 2014...

[The last few lines read:
In the last 21 days, have you experienced any of the following? Yes No
Have you been stuck with a needle used on an Ebola patient? [He checked No.]
Have you had body fluids of an Ebola patient in your eyes, nose or mouth? [He checked No.]
Have you taken part in a burial or funeral rites, or touched the body of someone who has died in an area where there is Ebola?
[He checked No.]
Did you stay in a house with or have other casual contact with an Ebola patient? [He checked No.]
Have you taken care of an Ebola patient or come into contact with body fluids of an Ebola patient? [He checked No.]
If your answer was yes, did you _always_ use a mask and gloves, and other protection? [He checked N/A (not applicable).]
Have you worked in a laboratory that processes body fluids of confirmed Ebola cases? [He checked No.]
If your answer was yes, did you _always_ use personal protective equipment? [He checked N/A (not applicable).]
http://www.gazettenet.com/living/health/13803096-95/family-who-hosted-ebola-patient-confined-to-home

[A defense lawyer might argue that he thought the sick woman he helped carry from the house he lived in had a serious case of malaria, and they took her 1st to the John F. Kennedy Memorial Hospital's maternity ward, so that he was truthful when he said he did not contact an Ebola patient, and anyway, he didn't touch her or go to her funeral after she died. - Mod.JW]

--
Nephew strongly rejected allegations that D. lied
----------------------------------------------------------------
3 Oct 2014: (CNN) Before flying out, D. allegedly answered "no" to questions on a health screening questionnaire about whether he'd cared for anyone with Ebola, or touched the body of someone who died in an area affected by the disease. But Tugbeh Chief Tugbeh, a community leader in Liberia, has said that D was "a caretaker" for a woman who died from Ebola at a residence outside the capital of Monrovia. Because of these and other claims, Liberia Airport Authority officials say they may prosecute D if he lied before leaving that West African nation...

D's nephew on Fri [3 Oct 2014] strongly rejected such allegations, much like other relatives have in recent days. Sitting alongside NG, D.'s mother, in Charlotte, North Carolina, D.'s nephew JW told CNN's Jim Sciutto that D. told him "he had moved a long time ago" from an area hit hard by Ebola. "He said, 'Well, I wasn't even in that area,'" said Weeks in direct response to Tugbeh's claim. "... He wasn't a part of that whole scenario that has been populating the news all these many days. So that's inaccurate."
http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/03/health/ebola-us-patient-family/index.html?iref=allsearch

[This is a conflicting, 2nd-hand story, repeated on CNN TV tonight, 6 Oct 2014. We shall see what transpires. - Mod.JW]

