[3] USA: sick cameraman arrives at Nebraska hospital
Date: 6 Oct 2014
Source: USA Today [edited]
http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/10/06/camerman-ebola-patient/16805529


An American freelance TV cameraman working for NBC News in West Africa walked off a plane today [6 Oct 2014], waving as he arrived in the USA for treatment after contracting Ebola in Liberia.

AM arrived Monday morning [6 Oct 2014] at the Nebraska Medical Center's special biocontainment unit in Omaha, one of 4 such units in the USA, which are all equipped to handle the most dangerous infectious diseases. Staff at these centers have undergone special training to handle Ebola and other biohazards for the past decade.

The video journalist, 33, reported symptoms on Wed [1 Oct 2014] and was running a slight fever. On Thu [2 Oct 2014], he was tested for the virus at a treatment center, with the result coming back positive, NBC News said in a story posted on its website... [His] parents said they haven't yet decided on the best treatment for their son. "We are assessing all treatment options," [said] Brad Britigan, dean of the college of medicine at the University of Nebraska Medical Center. Other Ebola patients treated in the USA have received experimental treatments, one of which is in short supply...

AM had been hired last Tue [1 Oct 2014] as a 2nd cameraman for NBC's medical correspondent, Nancy Snyderman, who is in Liberia reporting on the Ebola epidemic with 3 other NBC News employees... Snyderman and others in her crew will be flown back to the United States on a private charter flight and will be quarantined in the United States for 21 days "in an abundance of caution." http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/10/06/camerman-ebola-patient/16805529

[In fact, supplies of ZMapp are reported to be temporarily exhausted. - Mod.JW]

--
US journalist believes he got Ebola while cleaning infected car
----------------------------------
6 Oct 2014: (ABC News) The American journalist with Ebola who arrived at a Nebraska hospital today believes that he may have gotten infected when he got splashed while spray-washing a vehicle where someone had died from the disease. AM arrived at the Nebraska Medical Center this morning [6 Oct 2014] after being flown directly from Liberia. "He's strong and his symptoms are not more advanced than when he talked to us before he left, which is a relief," said his father ... at a news conference today. He said his [son] has a fever and slight nausea... Levy said that his son is "not certain" when he got the disease but believes that he could have gotten infected by some of the spray back that came when he was using chlorine [bleach] to disinfect a car. "It was a vehicle that somebody had died in," Levy said... http://abcnews.go.com/Health/us-journalist-ebola-nebraska-treatment/story?id=25987193

[Byline: Meghan Keneally]

